<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-361-38> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Western Apache bowl basket; coiled; willow, devil's claw; d. 23.5 cm., h. 8.5 cm.; ca. 1880.\r\nThis basket has a simple, elegant design of the type often described as interlocked stars, or petaled flowers, composed of black devil's claw curved lines radiating from the center. It apparently had a varied use-life, with a worn exterior, scorched on one side, and with residues of meal or pollen between stitches on the interior. It was collected in June/July 1883 at San Carlos or Camp Apache, Arizona.\r\n\tThe Western Apaches made wide, shallow bowls and ollas in the coiling technique. The Mescaleros produced similar trays in great quantities. Shallow and deep bowls were used for serving and preparing food. Often these exhibited no decoration as they soiled from the start and had a limited life-span. However, there are exceptions. In these cases two designs predominate: a fret/whirlwind/lightning pattern radiating outwards towards the rim from the black center, or floating a star/petal/flower motif (Whiteford 1988:57-58,78-79).\r\nThe baskets made by the different Apache tribes are quite distinct from one another, and from Navajo baskets, suggesting that each learned basket making from a different source. Late nineteenth- and early-twentieth-century Western Apache baskets, along with those made by Yavapai groups, are widely acknowledged as some of the finest, if not the finest baskets made during the historic era in the Southwest. Semi-nomadic groups often excel in the basketry arts: baskets are light-weight, strong, and do not break if dropped. Apaches used various types of baskets in most of the roles that pottery containers played for sedentary Puebloans.\r\n\r\n\tFor some reason, Ten Kate collected only a few Apache baskets. In one sense, this is unfortunate, in that it would have been wonderful to have had available in his collection some well-dated specimens. On the other hand, he may have understood that baskets were relatively commonplace, and concentrated on acquiring lesser-known items of material culture. The baskets he collected are representative examples of their kind, although several have interesting attributes. The four Mescalero baskets deserve closer analysis in that they exhibit a range of foundation construction techniques; Whiteford (1988:56-60) has discussed this aspect of Mescalero basket weaving and the questions surrounding its origins. Ten Kate's four baskets are a nice \"snapshot\" of techniques that were obviously in use simultaneously in 1883.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn het zuiden van Arizona worden meerdere stammen aangeduid als Western Apache.\r\nZij waren vooral bekend om het maken van manden met uitgebreide decoraties en het gebruiken van hel ingewikkelde technieken.\r\nDe gevlochten manden waren vaak gemaakt van wilgen en cottonwood, een soort populier.\r\nDe maand was zeer decoratief.\r\nVaak een rood kleuraardige grondstof rond de basis en de rand toegevoegd. Zelden werden rood of blauwe groene kleuren gebruikt.\r\nDe Apache stam stond vooral bekend voor het maken van potten ( in het Spaans ook wel olla's genoemd)\r\nSoms waren deze wel meer dan 12 meter hoog. \r\nOver het algemeen werden deze manden gemaakt voor de markt.\r\nHeel soms gebruikte de Apache deze manden voor het bewaren van mais.   \r\n\r\nAlgemene informatie:\r\nAls een rondreizen volk was het belangrijk voor de Apache stam dat er vooral potten en pannen waren die vooral minder snel braken.\r\nIn deze tijd (voor 1867)  werden er vooral potten met deksels van dierenhuiden en andere manden gemaakt. \r\nDeze werden gebruikt als waterkan of als opslag ruimte voor zaait en fruit. \r\nDe manden werden voornamelijk gemaakt van gras of hout.\r\nApache vrouwen maakten de manden voor eigen gebruik.\r\nVooral de  grote manden speelden een belangrijke rol in het leven van de stam. \r\nSoms werden de maanden ook gebruikt bij verschillende plechtigheden. \r\nBij een huwelijk ceremonie, bijvoorbeeld  werden de manden gevuld met voor de gasten.\r\nDe Navajo stam had wel een special rood/ zwart kleurig maand die enkel gebruikt werd bij een huwelijk ceremonie. \r\nThe Apache zijn erg nog steeds bekend voor het maken van  rieten manden. \r\nToch blijft het moeilijk om een bepaalde maand aan een stam toe te schrijven. Behalve dat de makers niet bekend waren   spelen er ander aspecten een rol. De  naai- en stick  techniek kan met name bepaalend zijn. Bovendien zijn de patronen op de manden zeer uiteen. \r\nEr kunnen bijvoorbeeld mensen, dieren, kruizen of steeren afgebeeld zijn. \r\nDeze afbeelding werden door allerlei stammen gebruikt.\r\nDe afbeeldingen hebben geen symbolische functie.\r\nWel worden er specifieke namen gegeven aan bepaalde ontwerpen.\r\nZo heet het patroon op deze mand \"Spider web\".\r\nIn de loop der tijd, verschenen er steeds meer kleine potjes en maanden.\r\nDeze werden voornamelijk gemaakt voor de handel met de Europeanen. \r\n\r\n \r\nEngelse tekst\r\n\r\nSouthwestern basket making\r\nIn Southwestern Arizona several tribal groups are described as Western Apaches.\r\nThey are particular known for the most elaborate  designs and techniques in basketry.\r\nTheir coiled baskets were made with three smoothed willow rods in a triangular foundation.\r\nThis would be sewn with fine splints of willow or less frequently with cottonwood. \r\nThe stiff narrow coils created a ridged surface.\r\nDecorations were done with black splints of devil's claw and occasional red yucca was used.\r\nThe center of the basket and also for rims are decorated with a red dye which was made from the plant called devils claw. \r\nVery seldom were red or blue-green dyed splints used in designs\r\nMost baskets were shallow bowl-trays.\r\nThe  Apache tribe was particularly  known for making jars(in Spanish referred to as: olla's.) Occasionally tall slender jars  would reach more than four feet.\r\nAlthough these baskets might have stored corn at one point or other, they were mainly  produced for the market.\r\nIt is a sad fact that by 1975 baskets were no longer made by some of the Southwestern tribes.\r\n However, in the1980s some woman have struggled to revive the art of twining baskets.  \r\n\r\nGeneral information\r\nAs nomadic peoples, vessels that are less prone to break became crucial to the Apaches. \r\nIn time, they produced baskets such as jars covered with buckskin to carry water or bowls to hold other household goods. \r\nThese baskets were usually made  from wood or grass. \r\nThe shape and size depended largely on what the basket where used for.\r\nWestern Apache baskets were usually made and designed by the Woman of the tribe. \r\nEach would produce a number of baskets for their own household purposes. \r\nLarge burden baskets played an important role in the Apache way of life.\r\nIn addition to practical purposes burden baskets were also used at ceremonies.\r\nOften these were filled with food for guests  or given as gifts.\r\nAlso the Navajo-tribe had a special red designed basket used at weddings.\r\nDuring the ceremony this basked was filled with corn and mush eaten by the broom , bride and quests. \r\nOften these basked were sold after the ceremonies.\r\nThe Apaches are very well known for making baskets.\r\nAlthough it still remains very difficult to prescribe a Western Apache coiled basket to a specific band. \r\nIt mainly depends on a complex and different stitching techniques used by the makers. \r\nDesign patterns are usually horizontal, vertical or may have whirling bands and many stylized figures of dogs, people, flowers or stars.\r\nEven though certain designs may have been given a specific name, they have no symbolic meaning. \r\nThis particular basket, for instance has a spider web design.\r\nThe design of the basket came from many different sources. \r\nMany times ideas for a design came from traditional patterns. Sometimes themes were borrowed from different tribes and the contact with missionaries influenced basket makers as well .\r\nAlso the materials and tools used in making  baskets played an important role.\r\nMany of the contemporary baskets such as miniature jars were made for commercial trade and catered to the white man's taste." .
